review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Shoe is lightweight and it feels nimble. Good for easy trails and speedy efforts. 
Pros:
Laces are good - had 5 different runs and never had to retie them. 
Traction is in line with expectations of 3-4mm lug depths - don't expect wonders on mud or thick layers of fallen leaves. 
Stable enough on uneven surface.

There few cons I would like to mention: 
The seam of the shoe fabric at the back forms a micro hump that can rub and lead to blisters. I had one after the first run, fixed that with putting plaster on my ankle.
Fabric on the top of the fingers was harder than I expected and I hope it will break in and be a a bit more softer. 
To ensure good lockdown I used runners knot and tong is barely enough to do it. A bit more padding in the inner side would be beneficial.
review.name: Light and nimble shoe for easy trails

review.itemreviewed: Terrex Agravic Speed Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
i am happy all the folks with positive reviews enjoying the shoes, but it didnt work for me at all. i've been a HUGE fan of the terrex speed ultra (which apparently has been discontinued). i was hoping these are replacements so i was super excited.

issues on my 20mi run.
- sizing is bigger compared to the speed ultra, so it was very loose and dangerous going down on technical trails, i did not feel comfortable going fast.
- the heel cup is too thin which makes it more unstable, and can lead to rolling ankles. the speed ultra had thicker heal cup (very nice).
- the upper was rubbing my foot, it was very painful on the down hill.
- the heel has that rocker feel which is kind of weird for me. i like the speed ultra which is just simple. but this rocker feel makes me feel like i am going to fall when i lean back.

the speed ultra was simple. the footing was very stable. if the agravic speed is supposed to be a replacement, then it definitely misses a lot. if this is not meant to be a replacement. i hope you (adidas) bring back the speed ultra (240). that was near perfect, just replace the foam and call it a new model and that would still be a winner.
review.name: unstable and uncomfortable

review.reviewBody:
This jacket was bought gor me as a gift about a month ago and I think I've worn it every day since, through November into December, in a wet and Stormy Wales.

The medium fits my 5'11" frame perfectly. Warmth isn't an issue. I've worn the jacket with only a t shirt beneath, in windy, freezing temps, with no issue at all. 
Lots of handy pockets and a hood that works best with a hat worn beneath.

Regarding rain. I'm not going to wear the jacket for prolonged rain. But for showers or drizzle my unwaxed jacket works just fine. For the time being I'm not going to wax it, as I like the way the jacket looks and I don't want to change that.

So a superb jacket for cold, windy, damp days. I love it.
review.name: Superb for Damp, Cold and Windy Wales.

review.reviewBody:
Had mine for over 14 months now and I really don’t like taking it off. It’s one of the warmest jackets I’ve ever had and definitely the comfiest, it’s like a sleeping bag. I had flu this winter and it was the only jacket I wanted to wear when going out…
There’s plenty pockets including hidden ones and most of them are zipped apart from the big inside ones which are really handy. 
The jacket is super adjustable especially round the head. I wasn’t looking for a completely waterproof jacket but it is showerproof … Never tested it in pouring rain (I love it too much) but even when it’s been raining the jacket stays super warm and doesn’t take long to dry out. This was the first Fjalraven product I’d owned and it’s definitely turned my attention to the brand. I love this coat so much I’m thinking of buying one in a different colour so that people don’t think I just own one coat. I have lots of designer jackets and coats that probably will catch people’s attention more but this is my ‘go to’, when the temperature drops.
review.name: Love this jacket

review.reviewBody: Very nice quality jacket. Read negative reviews about the zipper but have not had a problem with it personally. Warm enough for 95% of winter days.
review.name: Nice jacket

review.reviewBody: I'm very pleased with everything about this jacket. The quality and durability are excellent and I'm baffled by the reviews stating the zipper is of poor quality. My jacket is extremely well-built and there are no quality control issues. In fact, it's the opposite; this thing is built like a tank and I expect it will last for decades. I'm 5'10" and 165 with a muscular build and the medium fits great. I think the only thing that would change is to make the hood a little smaller since this jacket really isn't designed to be worn with the hood over a helmet. You can sinch the hood down to a snug fit, which is critical for me in a jacket, but if not tightened down, I would describe it as a helmet compatible hood given how large it is. The pockets are numerous and well-placed and the bottom draw string is also a critical included feature which keeps drafts out. This jacket is very warm and really blocks the wind. I feel protected when I wear it and am bummed that it's already spring time! Overall, I highly recommend this extremely well-crafted piece and I'm looking forward to years of use!
review.name: Extremely Durable and Functional

Fjallraven's sizing isn't ideal for me, but the Jacket fits great - a touch tight in lats, but still allows for layering, slightly long for me, but so is everything. The functionality of this jacket is second to NONE.  The pockets are spectacular (hand pockets, two exterior chest, and TWO interior chest with zippers, and two hat/glove pockets - perfection). The hood has great adjustability. Velcro cuffs are easy to adjust.  Zero issue with the two-way European Zipper - does not feel cheap. I do have the Singi in size M, and that thing is massive.

However, the arms are much too long and I find myself constantly fiddling with the wrist velcros trying to get them comfortable. This jacket needs shorter arms, and a thinner wrist velcro area, as the fabric bunches up and allows air in, while also being uncomfortable on bare skin. Additionally, the embroidery is already coming undone after about a week of wearing around town, and I have concerns about the quality of the zipper. Fjallraven, please take note of these concerns as this would be a perfect jacket otherwise.

review.reviewBody: Worth every penny! This slippers are so comfortable, warm and durable and I don't know why I wanted so long to get a pair. Warm feet are so important and Glerups are the best I have ever owned.
review.name: Fantastic!

review.reviewBody:
I work from home, and Central Oregon can get pretty cold, so slippers are a must for me. I've had many kinds of slippers, and these are by far my favorite.

A couple of years ago, some friends gave me a pair of these slippers with leather soles, which I found cool until I wore them so much that they smoothed out enough that the shoes slipped out from under me when I was coming downstairs. I wasn't hurt but didn't keep them.

A month or so ago I learned that they also came with rubber soles, which I got and are working out very well. The slipper themselves are great, warm, and (especially with the rubber sole) perfectly fine for the occasional trip outside the house.

If you don't have to deal with carpeted stairs, either sole will be good.
review.name: Great slippers but get the rubber sole

review.reviewBody:
As a born and raised New Englander, my moccasins had been tested in all conditions. Ultimately they were lost to the unentertained dog. Enter: The Glerup. Cozy enough to to work in all day while taking care of customers, and durable enough to play soccer with the doggos. 

Time will tell how they hold up, but so far so great! I wear a size 10.5 shoe and I went with the 44.0 they fit great. Not too snug, but snug enough to sprint after my blue heeler as he goes after a squirrel.
review.name: Move over mocassins

review.reviewBody: I have had these for three moths and wear them almost daily.  They were initially comfortable and warm, but mine have mostly worn out .  The interior bottom under the ball of my feet is already worn through almost to the sole, and they have shed most of their material. Considering getting myself a pair as well!

All of my previous Columbia fishing type shirts over the years have been in the medium size (I wear XL in all other brands, but Columbia shirts have previously run very large) as some recent reviews have indicated that Columbia has somewhat “normalized” their sizing. review.itemreviewed: Blood and Guts IV Woven Long-Sleeve Shirt - Men's
review.reviewBody:
As an avid angler, I've tried my fair share of fishing apparel, but none have impressed me as much as this long sleeve fishing shirt. It's safe to say that this garment is a game-changer for anyone who loves spending time on the water. Here's why:

The fit of this long sleeve fishing shirt is nothing short of perfection. It strikes that elusive balance between comfort and functionality. The shirt drapes smoothly over the body, allowing a full range of motion without feeling restrictive. Whether I'm casting a line or reeling in a catch, I never feel hindered by my clothing. It's almost as if it was tailor-made just for me.

This fishing shirt redefines practicality in fishing apparel. First and foremost, it's designed to protect from the sun's harsh rays, with a UPF rating that ensures my skin remains shielded during long hours under the sun. But what truly sets it apart are the pockets and added features.

When they say "lots of pockets," they mean it. This shirt is a veritable storage wonderland. Multiple pockets of varying sizes are strategically placed, allowing me to keep all my fishing gear organized and within easy reach. From tackle boxes to fishing line, there's a designated pocket for everything. 

The "bells and whistles" include features like built-in sunglass holders, ventilation ports to keep me cool, and roll-up sleeves with button tabs for quick adjustments when the temperature rises. It's clear that this shirt was designed by someone who understands the needs of a dedicated angler.

In addition to its practicality, this shirt is also stylish. It comes in a variety of colors and patterns, ensuring that you can look good while reeling in your next big catch.

Overall, this long sleeve fishing shirt is a must-have for any serious fisherman or outdoor enthusiast. Its remarkable fit, exceptional practicality, and the abundance of pockets and features make it an invaluable addition to your fishing arsenal. Whether you're casting lines for hours or simply enjoying a day on the water, this shirt has got you covered - literally and figuratively. It's the ultimate fishing companion, and I can't recommend it enough to fellow anglers.
review.name: A Fisherman's Dream: The Ultimate Long Sleeve Fish

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Just got back from first camping/portaging trip with this tent. Felt great for two humans and a dog, plenty of room to move around, and having two entrances is a game changer. Would def recommend.

review.reviewBody:
My first tungsten 3p tent was purchased approximately 10 years ago and has been very well used (and well taken care of). I decided to purchase a new Tungsten tent because I just couldn't get the water to bead away after waterproofing many times over the years (Kiwi Camp Dry and Wood's silicone waterproof spray). Also, the velcro tabs kept coming off even though I I glued them back on... and the tent clips (that attach to the poles) were starting to tear away from the screening. Anyway, it had served me very well and I accepted that these are the things that slowly start to break down after many years of use.

In setting up my new Tungsten tent, I instantly noticed the quality of materials did not match up to my old version of this tent. Material is finer (feels thinner), all of the strapping and buckles are smaller and there is just an overall feeling of cheapness to the tent. 

I've only been on a 5 day trip so far and it kept me dry. And I do appreciate the improvement with moving from plastic to aluminum for the piece that ties the main poles together. I expect it will serve it's purpose but just disappointed in the loss of quality in materials. I also suspect that it will not last as long as my old version.

One last gripe, there are 8 points of tie down on the tent itself plus 4 more to secure the fly in high winds, for a total of 12 tent pegs required, so why does the tent only come with 6 pegs.

I weighed the tent and fly and there is only a 5 gram difference between the old and new, so cutting quality on the materials wasn't to reduce weight.

Very disappointed, I used to rave about this tent to everyone I knew but will no longer be recommending it unless the quality in materials is improved upon.
review.name: Lesser quality than older Tungsten version

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The Tungsten 3P tent held up in light rain and heavy wind on a backpacking trip along the west coast. review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] We were just camping in the Swiss Alps at a festival and we had the most insane storms roll through with lightening/thunder and torrential downpours. It was so much rain that a massive landslide happened after this storm. This tent was in 4-5 inches of water for an hour or so until we could move it to higher ground with a break in the storm. We were were amazed and so thankful that all of our gear was dry. We ended up getting another intense storm roll in a couple hours later with rain and wind so intense it destroyed some of the other festival goers tents and canopy's. This second storm hit later at night and our only option was to ride it out in the tent. We were sitting on our air mattresses and could push on the bottom of the tent and feel several inches of water below it. We were definitely scared we would wake up the next morning in water with everything wet but this tent was amazing! When we woke up the next morning it was damp under both of our sleeping mats but everything else stayed dry. Incredible! The wind and rain was truly intense. I'd never experienced that level of storm in a tent before. I was sure either the tent would collapse or it would get blown away. I'm truly impressed with this tent! It is the first Marmot I have owned and I highly recommend!
review.name: Incredible tent for weathering intense storms!

review.reviewBody: I got these boots specifically because of the Hoji Lock system being introduced to a full on hybrid boot with gripwalk. The flex is pretty dang solid, so I am comfortable using these as a 50/50 boot in and out of the resort. The thing I was blown away by was the functionality of the walk mode. It's so nice that the power strap and both upper buckles are connected to the walk mode lever. The interface of the liner tongue and the overlapping shell is really nice, too. They're relatively easy to get into and quite comfortable liner-wise. My last is around a 103-104mm and I did need to punch them right at the "6th toe." My boot fitter mentioned the plastic being exceptionally easy to work with and I am quite pleased with the fit post molding. I did not mold the liner, as it seems fairly easy to break in over the course of a couple of ski tours. I'm very pleased with the uphill performance of this boot in particular. With Tigard 130 Dynafit hit the sweetspot and I now have a "do it all boot"

review.reviewBody:
I bought this boot principally to wear as a quick slip-on boot for taking my dog on neighborhood walks and out on potty breaks, so for that purpose it serves its purpose pretty well. It's warm for my feet down into the single digits and the Vibram sole grips well in snow and on light ice. Cushioning is good, but not stellar. Waterproofing in several months of wear is excellent.

Given it's construction though, I wouldn't recommend this for hiking purposes as Danner suggests it's useful for, it's way too lacking in support for that, or even robust, fast trail walking - its upper is splashy and not super supportive, even factoring the internal heel support, so it would be very easy to roll an ankle in these.

review.reviewBody: Took my 70L on two dirty, sandy multi-day trips: Desolation Canyon on the Green, and a month in the Grand Canyon. For the latter trip, I used this as my day-to-day bag to access my tent, camp clothes, small camp chair, etc.. I was fearful about the zipper getting compromised with all the sand and frequent access. It didn't fail on me once- and it withstood my constant stuffing it to the gills with last minute stuff. Highly recommend to folks who want something they can trust and are tired of getting cramped hands from other types of closures. I do recommend keeping a toothbrush and some T-Zip handy just in case. Also loved the backpack feature for fewer trips unloading the boats!
review.name: My Favorite Daily Use Bag

review.reviewBody: Zipper broke after one trip.  Send request for warranty replacement and they said they'd get back to me in 4 months.  Finally I bugged them enough they said just to send it in. review.reviewBody: Tough stuff. Waterproof! Easy to pack, load and carry. Held bulk of gear (not food) for a 8-day paddle in the North Cascades. Fits perfectly crosswise in a 18' Jesen canoe (narrow boat). Should fit most any tandem canoe. Carry straps work great for short distances, I might consider a pro pack for longer portages, but up to a mile or so should be fine. Appreciate the straps to tie on extra stuff. Would be nice to have a couple of simple interior pockets, but using multiple stuff sacks works fine and is more versatile.
review.name: Great canoe pack for longer trips

And easy to secure and lock with built in cable lock! Light  weight easy to carry and store! Love the hitch instal locking feature makes for secure fit each ltime installing on auto highly recommend.kuat

review.reviewBody: I just purchased a new triathlon bike, and with the carbon fiber frame, I feel confident my bike is safe and secure on this bike rack. The pricing was reasonable, as the accessories that come with ensure my bike doesn’t move or get scratched.
review.name: Great design, Easy Setup, and Protective

review.reviewBody: I bought this recently after looking at some other options from Kuat. Due to being in the same town as the company it is a very popular local brand around here. The Sherpa is the lightest of the racks I looked at which is great if it won’t just be left on the vehicle. I also bought their kayak racks and when I wanted all of the lock cylinders to match all I had to do was reach out to them and they handled right at their local no questions asked. The quality and ease of use is great, but this one is not expandable for more bike unlike others they make.
review.name: Great company

review.reviewBody: This rack is what I was hoping for. Minimal. No bells and whistles. Just a solid, reliable bike rack. Light weight. 15 lbs less than my OG Kuat rack. Kuat knows how to do it.
review.name: Light weight. Low profile

review.reviewBody:
I bought this to replace my RockyMounts SplitRail, which perished in a rear-end accident. 
I really like the Sherpa aesthetically--it's compact and clean. I don't like the pivot lever at all. No matter what, it requires two hands or a hand and a foot. The SplitRail (and most Thule & Yakima racks) have an easy-to-use lever that can be used with one hand. Usually when I need to open my hatch, it's b/c I have armloads of stuff to put in there, and this requires me to put things down to pivot the rack and open the hatch. I'd call it a minor design flaw.
If the the SplitRail were still available, I would've gone with that, but I'm still happy w/ this purchase overall.
review.name: Nearly perfect

review.reviewBody: This is by far the best bike rack I've owned!  Very well engineered.  The box was even designed to aid in assembly!  Very easy to use, very light and excellent construction.  Fits all of our bikes with different frame styles.  My old rack was difficult to mount bikes with square carbon tubing, and mountain bikes with sloping top tubes.  This rack fits them all.
review.name: Easiest to use and lightweight!

review.reviewBody: I research a lot before a purchase. Sometimes to the point of analysis paralysis.  After comparing this to other brands and asking other riders at an event a few weeks ago it was an easy decision.
review.name: Just Buy It - You Won't Regret

review.reviewBody: Love my Sherpa!  Agree with other 5 star reviews.  Easy to load bikes which gets me out of the house faster. Looks great and seems well built.
review.name: Rack Gets Me to Ride More

I really liked this tent for the first couple of years that I had it. I didn't use but 6-7 times a year so I figured it would last a long time. Fast forward to this year and one of my poles break during set up. Big time bummer!

So, great tent, great design with the 2 doors and vestibules, etc. But a broken pole is no good. Did Eureka go cheap on materials?

review.reviewBody: We used the Midori a few weekends ago...38°F and windy the first night. Tent held up well. Sizable vestibule for our motorcycle boot, etc. Next night slightly warmer. Tent was easy to set up (i set up previously at home).  Seems sturdy. No issues. Four inside pockets for headlamps, etc. Comes with a storage hammock for above your head. Perfect for two people for multiple nights, would be okay for three for one night at a time. All good 😀
review.name: Great tent

review.reviewBody: I have used this tent for over a year.  The best part for me is having a door on both sides.  I am in my mid 60s and getting in and out of a tent takes a little...okay, a lot more effort than it used too.  With 2 people in the tent, you both have a door.  If something happened to this tent, I would buy another just like it the next day.

review.reviewBody:
I initially bought the Midori 2 for solo camping, and liked it so much that I bought the Midori 3 for trips with my husband, and absolutely love both of them!  Most recently the Midori 3 went with us for 9 nights of camping to the Grand Tetons, Yellowstone, and some spots en route - it's roomy enough for 2 people with some gear (and bulkier "luxury" sleeping pads), especially with the 4 pockets pockets and massive gear loft to keep smaller items in check. 
 It's unfailingly easy to set up and tear down, and performed magnificently in a windy Nebraska thunderstorm, remaining completely dry inside.  It rained overnight on three occasions, and each time we (and our stuff) stayed completely dry.  The vestibules are a good size for shoes and any errant wet gear.  The ventilation system is awesome - we were able to test it out on a muggy overnight in July, and we stayed far more comfortable than we had in a previous popular entry-level tent.  The footprint is definitely worth the purchase as well, though I do wish it came with the tent outright.  All in all, 10/10 tent!
review.name: Love this tent (and the Midori 2)!

review.reviewBody: Iv only used this tent once so far, on a ten mile over night backpacking trip on the Florida trail. but it was a perfect fit for me and my dog and plenty room to move around. The tent provided ample protection from the insects and morning dew. Will be using this tent more during fall and winter it’s to hot for camping.
review.name: Easy setup, and tear down

review.reviewBody: Although I have only used this tent once I am thrilled about the high quality especially for such a great price. In the past, I have worked as a backpacking guide and had experience with several types of tents (one pole vs. 2/3/4 pole). This tent is easy to set up, durable, and looks really cool too. I am very impressed.
review.name: Excellent all around

As a result is now a bit large but actually works well. Hood also stows so good for running if you just want to keep the wind off. review.reviewBody: I hate leaving a bad review and I'm sorry for this but I need to be honest. I only wore this jacket 3 times in heavy rain for no longer than 5 minutes at a time while running errands. Within a minute or 2 the arms began to wet out. When I took the jacket off there was definitely moisture on my arms. Although my core was dry, the jacket immediately began absorbing water and I could tell that if I wore it for any significant amount of time, the entire jacket would wet out.  The jacket doesn't repell water. It begins absorbing it immediately and I had to hang it up for at least an hour to dry. I know most ultralight jackets will eventually wet out but not after 5 minutes. For the price, I would expect to  be able to at least wear it for a few hours in the rain before wetting out. I have the yellow version from last year so maybe there have been some improvements but all of the specs appear to be the same as the current version. Most of the other reviews seem to be positive so perhaps I was unlucky and got a defective one. I bought this for an ultralight back packing jacket but definitely would not trust it on a hike in the back country.  As far as size, the jacket runs a bit small as it has a sporty fit. If you plan on wearing it as a shell, I would definitely size up. Again, I'm sorry for the negative review as I know Rab makes some good products.
review.name: Wet out quick

review.reviewBody:
Used for: winter snowshoeing/hiking at -5 C to 10 C (sometimes with rain pants but usually just with running shorts), downhill skiing at 0 C (underneath insulated snow pants)

Warmth: Excellent during intense activity. The fabric is thin but very breathable. Sweat never accumulates, even while climbing steep slopes. It's slightly thinner, hence more breathable, in specific areas: below the knees and along the sides of the hips and thighs. The trade-off is that it leaves me more sensitive to wind chill than my thicker, 100% wool tights do. I can fix that by throwing on a shell, however.

Fit: Got the Small (I'm a skinny 5'7"/170 cm). It's tighter on the legs than expected, but still fairly comfortable. The waistband sits maybe an inch lower than I'd like for winter layering and I'm too skinny to keep it from slipping down when I try to pull it all the way up.

Quality: No wear and tear after several uses in one winter season. Stays odorless thanks to the breathability and merino wool blend.

Overall: This is now my go-to bottom for intense outdoor activities around 0 C. I would opt for something thicker if temperatures dropped far below freezing or in heavy winds.
review.name: Good quality and warmth for intense winter days

review.reviewBody: Bought a CX bike about 6 months ago & it had these tires on it (38c). Initially, I liked the tires, but I was considering buying something a bit narrower because most of my riding was going to be on paved roads and only a little bit of gravel. After putting about 1,500 miles on the bike, I can confidently say that I would repurchase these tires in a heartbeat! They’re so fast on pavement, I honestly don’t think going narrower would change much. They also have performed exceptionally well on gravel, and I even took them on a gravel century ride I did a few weeks ago and they were excellent!  My girlfriend’s bike has terravail Washburns on it & they just aren’t quite the same. The narrower smooth section in the center of tire has considerably more resistance than the more generous smooth section on these. Also have been good in wet conditions. Truth is, most of the pavement here In Minneapolis kinda sucks, & I’d rather float over it on 38s than a 25c or even 30c any day. Bottom line- If you want a tire that can do it all and still be fast on tarmac, this is it.
review.name: Cannot Recommend These Tires Enough!

review.reviewBody: I have an ebike (Ride1Up 700 series) and decided to purchase this bag for my daily commute to work. It is an excellent bag - it carries everything I need (computer, lunch, water bottle, jacket, and shoes) and has keep it perfectly dry when biking in the rain. The backpack is comfortable to wear as well.
review.name: Great daily bag for work commute

review.reviewBody: I bought this bag for my daily commuting, to upgrade my 15yo ortlieb classic panniers with something I could more easily walk a few blocks with. So far the bag has been good in terms of being easy to load on the bike, and the conversion from pannier to backpack is relatively easy. It looks good for a 'pannier backpack', except for my one gripe with this bag. The problem involves the fabric flap that you move from back to front when converting between bike/back. The fabric is held on with 3 little fittings, but two of them are just a plastic piece that goes into a gap in fabric, with nothing that securely grabs them. It's very easy for the plastic pieces to become free of the fabric, which means that the fabric flap piece of my bag is always flopping around.
review.name: Fine bag, with one annoying issue

review.reviewBody:
I just got back into bike commuting for the first time in many years and was looking for a LARGE single pannier that could be converted into a backpack for ease of carrying in and out of work, waterproof, yet still be able to carry a few toiletries, a full change of clothes with shoes, and my lunch. I found exactly what I hoped for in the Ortlieb Vario PS with 26 Liter capacity. Backcountry not only offered the best price, but also had all of the colors the Vario PS comes in, in stock (except maybe yellow?)! I chose the “Dark Sand” color which is very accurate in the pictures shown on Backcountry.com.

The Vario PS has plenty of room for everything I need to be ready for work and has room for my laptop and a towel, as well. The quality is excellent and it looks great.The outer fabric is “water resistant” but the inside of the bag is water proof (if closed properly by rolling it down and buckling it). Ortlieb includes 3 sets of “hook” adapters to accommodate the smaller circumference / rail thickness of whichever type of rear rack you’ve got. The hooks on the Vario PS are quite large (16 mm?) and the 3 sets of hook adapters are 8, 10, and 12 mm. 14 mm(?) adapters are also available but are a separate charge, IIRC. These are so your Vario doesn’t rattle around on your rack (the adapters allow for a more snug fit on your rack rails which also helps prevent it from sliding out of place).

The Vario PS drops onto your rack very easily by just holding it / lifting / pulling up the carrying strap handle, which opens up the hooks and all you need to do is place it on your rack in the position you want (so your heel doesn’t hit it while you’re pedaling). In order to remove it from the rack, just pull up on the carrying strap handle which opens up the hooks and lift it off of your rack.

I purchased the one with the QL2.1 fastening system as it’s tried and true, rather than the new(er) QL3.1 system (although, judging from YT videos, the QL3.1 seems as though it might pretty darned good, as well). Watch some YT videos for a demonstration of these systems.

There is a hard plastic “clamp” on a guide rail located on the exterior lower end of the bag which faces your wheel. You’ll need to adjust its position by loosening a thumb wheel screw and place it so that it goes around the inside of your rack’s vertical support, which is intended to prevent the (lower end of the) bag from flopping around thereby keeping the bag securely affixed and aligned on your rear rack.

There is a reversible “flap” / cover on the bag which conceals the backpack shoulder straps so they’re not flapping around in the wind while you’re riding. Simply unlatch the cover hook from a fastening loop on the side of the bag and pull the cover downward diagonally around to the other side of the bag and fasten the hook to a loop which will then conceal the part of the back that faces your wheel while riding. Just a really thoughtful piece of engineering!

The only potential (small) “flaw” I have identified with the Vario PS is that it doesn’t come with a rain cover. And why should it, you may ask? The exterior fabric is water resistant and the interior is water proof. The shoulder straps, while “covered” by the flap when you’re riding, will get wet if you get caught in the rain or riding on a wet trail and water or dirt gets kicked up because the flap does not fit OVER the top part of the bag. This means that you potentially cannot wear the backpack without either getting your clothes wet / dirty or drying / cleaning the straps and back side first before strapping it to your back (if you’re wearing the Vario PS in backpack mode and you’re caught in the rain there isn’t much you can do to prevent the shoulder straps and side that’s against your back from getting wet).

I solved this problem by getting a waterproof backpack cover (Amazon) to put over the top and outer side of the Vario PS which covers the top and the outside part of the bag (not the wheel side) that’s covered by the flap where the concealed backpack shoulder straps are located.

Overall, great bag, though quite pricey, but would buy again, if I ever needed to. Kudos also to Backcountry for having a broad number of sizes and colors in stock to choose from, easy ordering process and FAST shipping!
review.name: Perfect for Commuting!

review.reviewBody: If you're on the fence about what size to get, they seem large relative to the claimed capacity. The 20L is a pretty big backpack on me. I can comfortably fit my laptop and accessories, lunch, a change of clothes, and an extra jacket in it. The 26L is really huge (I saw it in-person at REI) which would be nice if you're going to use it for your grocery shopping or if you take a ton of stuff commuting, but for my purposes it would generally be too much (keeping in mind I'm not a large person)
review.name: just what I was looking for, pretty big

review.reviewBody:
Shoes are like saddles...obviously very personal choices given that they're just one of three contact points we have with our bikes.  After decades of wearing Sidis (and my feet always going numb towards the end of longer rides), I began a search to find a cycling shoe that would allow my forefoot/toes to splay out a bit more (much like the running shoes/sneakers I was buying did...Keens, Altras, Topos).  When I first got a pair of Lake's CX238s a few years ago, my riding enjoyment exponentially increased just from the comfort alone...was a bonus that Lake makes some good looking shoes as well.

Fast forward to this fall/winter when I purchased a gravel bike, the list of potential shoes was a fairly short one...the MX238s (the ruggedized version of my CX238s).  That being said, with my better half not always the most supportive of my hobby/habit, I was looking at some other options/brands to possibly save some money when picking up the needed accoutrements to go with the new bike (when I broke the news that I had ordered this latest bike, was informed that we now had to have our master bath redone).  All feet are different so it's often hard to wade through all of the reviews...and with how much a solid pair of cycling shoes cost a negative review or two definitely makes you think twice...and despite the couple of negative reviews on the MX238s, decided to stick with my gut feeling and am happy that I did.

The MX238 is a solid cycling shoe.  They (probably more so their 'competition' last/foot form) work great on MY feet (YMMV) and I've never had any issues with heel slippage or the Boa wire causing any discomfort (I'm basing a lot of this on my experience with the CX238s, but so far, no issues with the MX238s either).  When I first received this new pair of shoes, it took me several weeks to commit to them before I finally put the cleats on them (they just felt a little different from my road shoes)....but, after a few rides (admittedly all just on the trainer), I'm confident that in time they'll be just as awesome as my CX238s which after several seasons feel like an old comfortable pair of slippers (the leather uppers on a good many of Lake's shoes just get better with age).

Just to talk a bit more about fit/sizing...as mentioned above, my feet can sometimes be a bit tough to buy shoes for.  I'd been a fan of Sidis for a long time (almost three decades) but they started hurting my feet (along with any other shoe that was a bit snug on the forefoot).  I don't have a wide foot nor does it take up a lot of volume (think vertical girth)....but, it definitely likes to have room to splay out these days.  I don't have a lot of arch either...and while Lakes have some arch support, it's not as pronounced as some and still works for my flat feet.  Lake makes several different lasts/foot forms so if considering one of their shoes, you definitely want to go to their website and research which one might work best for your foot shape.  Their sizing guides are fairly intuitive and straight forward...I was able to get into my right 'Lake' size/last on the first try.
review.name: Lakes are my go-to shoe...

review.reviewBody: Bought these shoes and immediately experienced the heel slipping that I read about in other reviews. Ended up buying and keeping the MX333 instead which didn't have this issue as much. The lake sizing guide on their website worked well- I definitely recommend using it.
review.name: Heel slip is real

review.reviewBody: Roomy, great power transfer to pedal and very comfortable. The wide version makes all the difference. I’d recommend it for normal width feet and bigger. Went up a half size and I love it
review.name: Best MTB shoe I’ve used

review.reviewBody: I bought the MX238 size 43.5 Wide, with the recommendation of a bike fitter.  I have bought many others that were too tight. Unlike the other reviews my foot and heel fit perfectly. My last shoes were 45 Shimano, they felt good, but when I placed my foot on the insert, it was more than an inch longer. This is bad for cleat and pedal placement. As the Brits and Irish say, Happy Days!
review.name: Love these shoes

review.reviewBody: This is the first pair of cycling shoes that fit me and fit me perfectly. They are so comfortable, even with the extremely stiff sole.
review.name: Runs true to size

review.reviewBody:
Great fit for wide feet, but the laces from the BOA closure closest to my ankle dig into the top of my foot causing discomfort. To get relief, I have to have just about zero tension in the laces which leads to the heel coming out of the shoe. The front BOA closure works fine and the laces don't cause any discomfort. With an old pair of Specialized S-Works shoes, I cut out the padding from the tongue of the shoes and put it under the tongue of the MX238s - the pain went away regardless of the tension I put into the BOA. Great! Now, I'd have to pay a cobbler to put more padding in the tongue of these shoes to make them wearable. Unfortunately, I did not discover this until putting the cleats on and riding for an hour. Wearing them around the house did not reveal the problem.
Don't make the mistake I have made. The thin BOA laces will cut into your foot without adequate padding to disperse the tension from the cables.
review.name: Great for wide feet, but...

review.reviewBody: Less than a year after purchasing, these shoes are so noisy I?m ready to toss them in the trash. I chased a noise for a month that I thought was coming from the bike only to finally learn it?s coming from the shoe itself. I tried new cleats, new pedals, and even a different bike. Noise follows me everywhere. These shoes are expensive, and while nice- should not be this annoying after less than a year. I reached out to Lake, and was disappointed in their customer service. My previous Pearl?s were 3 years old and never made a peep. I can not recommend these shoes.
review.name: Creaky!

review.reviewBody: I had hunted for a long time to find a MTB shoe to fit my EEE width forefoot and skinny heal/ankle and read a ton of great things about this shoe.  When I first put them in my living room on I was so excited as they fit perfectly then I stood up and my heal almost came out of the back.  I tried everything to fix it (different socks, tightening down the BOA) and nothing worked so I had to return them and keep searching.
review.name: Heal lift is real (ly bad)

review.reviewBody: I love EVERTHING about this shoe, BUT although I wanted more forefoot room for my toe-warmers in winter riding... my foot, probably average for a size 41 shoe female, is still lower volume than most males. So...not only was my foot was moving around a bit, but the dreaded heel slip was also unacceptable, especially for a person used to older model SIDIs which fit like the proverbial glove.  I would have purchased SIDIs again,  but HATE their new Tech-NO closure system (Hello...I live in the northweat and those are NOT manageable when wearing long-fingered gloves)! LAKES: PLEASE MAKE SOME WOMEN'S MODELS!!
review.name: Lakes: Please make a women's shoe!!

review.reviewBody:
First attempt: had to return these. the size information on the product page for competitive cyclist says size 44 equates to a 10.  When the Lake shoes came they said size 44 and 11 on the box.  They were too big of course. 

Edit - received the right size; 43.  Fit is good, until you want to walk or pedal.  The heel slip on these shoes is something I've never felt in a shoe; cycling or not.  Should have listened to reviews on this page. The heel slip is real and too much.
review.name: major heel slip

name: MX238 Cycling Shoe - Men's

review.itemreviewed: Nucleo High II GTX Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
This is the first boot in my 50 years of hiking that have worked very well in all hiking conditions without giving me blisters!!!  Every leather or other lightweight boot I've used have given me serious blisters within an hour out on the trail carrying a heavy pack.  I tried every sock, lacing combination and nothing has worked.  These boots are 2 lbs. lighter than my leather boots and the Vibram soles are the best and sticky soles that I've worn.  Just returned from a camping trip carrying a 52 lb. pack (had to bring in water) and my feet are blister free and happy.  Good ankle support.  The lacing system is good and thoughtful.  Very comfortable boot with an option insole that I added.  I stood in a stream for 5 minutes and not a drop inside.  After a long day hiking my socks only had a minimun amout of dampness in them which is normal in any boot.  
Way to go La Sportiva!
review.name: Great boots

review.itemreviewed: Nucleo High II GTX Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I have weak ankles from years of soccer and need supportive boots. These are a rare find these days, as they are day hikers with high ankle support. I had used Vasque Sundowners for years but they just weren't cutting it anymore. At first I ordered a pair of Mammut Duncan High GTX which were incredibly supportive and I wanted so badly to keep them because of that but they were just too narrow for my troll feet. So on to my first pair of La Sportivas  These gave me that instant feeling of stepping into clouds. A boot that fits from the first moment you stick your feet in.  These are wide enough for me yet still wrap up my ankles enough to feel confident on tricky terrain. The Mammut's do have this unique wrapping on the upper section that was superior but I guess you can't have everything. Also, the La Sportivas lace eyes on the upper section are a bit annoying because I like to lace from above to hold the knot better and I can't do that with these - but I can adapt. I've only done about 20 miles in these so far but after each hike or forage, my dogs aren't barking! So happy with these.
review.name: Love these boots!

review.itemreviewed: Nucleo High II GTX Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
The build quality seems great, and they look fantastic. I bought it for its waterproofness, but I never got out of the indoor testing phase. It is extremely uncomfortable to wear and I had to order three sizes above my normal to be able to handle the width of my feet. My normal size (they are European sizes only, I am in North America) wasn't fitting at all and hurt my feet. I ordered three different sizes over the course of a month. I normally am a 44, but I order 45 and 44.5 with no satisfaction. They are too narrow in width, but primarily too short in terms of the height of one's foot. It would hurt the skin on the top of my foot, and the heel and toes wouldn't touch in sizes that fit my foot width. I have wider feet than normal, but not massively so. I returned all sizes, since every single one hurt my feet in slightly different ways. 

I would only recommend if your feet are very short, long in length, and narrow in width. Like a turkey or cassowary foot is what I ended up telling people in person.
review.name: Very narrow and runs long

name: Nucleo High II GTX Boot - Men's
